{"title_page": "Vivian E. Browne", "text_new": "{{Infobox artist\n| honorific_prefix = \n| name             = Vivian E. Browne<!-- include middle initial, if not specified in birth_name -->\n| honorific_suffix = \n| image            = Vivian E. Browne.jpg<!-- just the pagename, without the File:/Image: prefix or [[brackets]] -->\n| image_size       = 200px\n| alt              = \n| caption          = \n| native_name      = \n| native_name_lang = \n| birth_name       = <!-- only use if different than name -->\n| birth_date       = {{Birth date|1929|04|26}}\n| birth_place      = [[Laurel, Florida]], [[United States]]\n| death_date       = {{Death date and age|1993|07|23|1929|04|26}} \n| death_place      =[[Manhattan]], [[New York (state)|New York]], United States\n| resting_place    = \n| resting_place_coordinates = <!-- {{Coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline}} -->\n| nationality      = American\n| education        = [[Hunter College]]\n| known_for        = Painting\n| notable_works    = \n| style            = \n| movement         = \n| spouse           = \n| awards           = <!-- {{awd|award|year|title|role|name}} (optional) -->\n| elected          =\n| patrons          = \n| memorials        = \n| website          = <!-- {{URL|Example.com}} -->\n| module           =\n}}\n'''Vivian E. Browne''' (April 26, 1929&ndash;July 23, 1993) was an American artist. Born in [[Laurel, Florida]], Browne was mostly known for her African-American protest paintings, and linking abstraction to nature. She has received multiple awards for her work, been an activist, professor and a founder of many galleries. According to her mother, Browne died at 64 from [[bladder cancer]].<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n==Biography==\nVivian Browne was born in [[Laurel, Florida]], on April 26, 1929.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.thecrowsneststudio.com/artists/196-2/vivian-e-browne-cv/|title = Vivian E. Browne CV|website = The Crows Nest Studio|language = en-US|access-date = 2016-03-05}}</ref> She spent most of her life in [[New York City]] and [[Kern County]], [[California]]. She received her [[Bachelor of Science]] in 1950 from [[Hunter College]], New York, NY and a [[Master of Fine Arts]] from [[Hunter College]] in 1959. Her early painting career was fostered by a scholarship from the [[New School for Social Research]], and a [[Huntington Hartford Foundation]] fellowship in 1964 and a fellowship with the [[MacDowell Colony]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nShe was invested in her travels across [[Europe]] and [[Africa]], also studying at the [[University of Ibadan]] in [[Nigeria]] in 1972. Browne worked at [[Rutgers University]] in Newark from 1971 to 1992 as a faculty member of the Arts and Sciences department while continuing as an artist in her own right with shows across the country.\n\n== Career ==\nBrowne had multiple solo exhibitions at [[Soho20 Chelsea|SoHo 20 Gallery]] during her lifetime, as well as exhibitions at the [[Bronx Museum of the Arts|Bronx Museum]], [[University of California, Santa Cruz]] and [[Western Michigan University]].<ref>{{Cite book|title=North American Women Artists of the Twentieth Century: A Biographical Dictionary|last=Heller|first=Jules and Nancy G.|publisher=Routledge|year=1997|isbn=978-0815325840|location=Abingdon-on-Thames|pages=}}</ref> She also showed at [[MoMA PS1]]'s space in the Clocktower Gallery in 1986.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.moma.org/calendar/exhibitions/4416?locale=en|title=Progressions: A Cultural Legacy|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Browne was posthumously included in the exhibition ''We Wanted a Revolution: Black Radical Women, 1965\u201385,'' organized by the [[Brooklyn Museum]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.contemporaryartdaily.com/2017/09/group-show-at-brooklyn-museum/|title=Group Show at Brooklyn Museum|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> In 2018, her work was also shown in ''Acts of Art and Rebuttal in 1971'', an exhibition at [[Hunter College]] that revisited the 1971 exhibition ''Rebuttal to the Whitney Museum Exhibition: Black Artists in Rebuttal'' organized by members of the  Black Emergency Cultural Coalition to protest the [[Whitney Museum of American Art|Whitney Museum]]\u2019s refusal to appoint a Black curator for their survey ''Contemporary Black Artists in America''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://huntercollegeartgalleries.org/events/2018/rebuttal|title=Acts of Art and Rebuttal in 1971|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Browne had been considered for the Whitney's exhibition but was ultimately not included.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://brooklynrail.org/2018/11/artseen/Acts-of-Art-and-Rebuttal-in-1971|title=Acts of Art and Rebuttal in 1971|last=Pobric|first=Pac|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==Collections==\nBrowne's work is housed in public and private collections all over the United States, primarily in New York and California. Most notably her work can be found in the collections of the [[Smithsonian]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://americanart.si.edu/collections/search/artist/?id=624|title=Artworks Search Results / American Art|website=americanart.si.edu|access-date=2016-03-05}}</ref> with the [[Robert Blackburn (artist)]] printmaking workshop, [[MOMA]],<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.moma.org/learn/resources/archives/ps1_artists/artists_b5|title = MoMA {{!}} MoMA PS1 Artists|website = www.moma.org|access-date = 2016-03-05|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20151012011833/http://www.moma.org/learn/resources/archives/ps1_artists/artists_b5#|archive-date = 2015-10-12|url-status = dead}}</ref> the [[Schomburg Center]] NYC, [[Chase Manhattan Bank]]  the [[John Cotton Dana Library]], the Hatch-Billops Collection, the [[Wadsworth Atheneum]] Museum, The [[New York Public Library]]  and the [[Harry Belafonte]] & [[Rosa Parks]] private collections.<ref name=\":1\">Hamalian, L.. (1985). Talking to Vivian Browne. Black American Literature Forum, 19(1), 48\u201350. http://doi.org/10.2307/2904481</ref> Browne is included in the Center for the Women in the Arts and Humanities virtual exhibit at [[Rutgers University]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cwah.rutgers.edu/programs/mary-h-dana-women-artists-series/40-years-of-women-artists-at-douglass-library/virtual-exhibit/#B|title=Center for Women in the Arts and Humanities|website=cwah.rutgers.edu|access-date=2016-03-05}}</ref>\n\n==Activism==\nMany of Browne's works, particularly those from the 1960s, showcase her dissatisfaction with the struggles of growing up as a [[Disfranchisement|disenfranchised]] black woman. \"Black art is political. If it's not political, it's not black art\".<ref name=\":1\" /> While she fought for equality, she was not optimistic about attitudes changing soon, and self categorized her look at art into two categories. \"When I am political, I am painting as a black or as a woman or both. Otherwise, I am just a member of the human race.\" She taught the History of Black Art at [[Rutgers University]], and served as chair of the department from 1975 to 1978. \n\nBrowne contributed to, and served as an advisor to, ''[[Heresies: A Feminist Publication on Art and Politics|HERESIES: A Feminist Publication on Art and Politics]]'', including serving on the editorial collective for issue #15, Racism is the Issue. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://archive.org/stream/heresies_20/heresies_20_djvu.txt|title=Full text of \"Heresies Magazine Issue #20: Heresies (Volume 5, Number 4)\"|website=archive.org|access-date=2016-03-05}}</ref>\n\n==Major Achievements==\nIn addition to serving as a professor and department chair at [[Rutgers]], Browne was honored most notably for her political works showcasing her life as a black woman. She served as a [[Fulbright]] panelist in 1990, and spent much of her time in the 70s and 80s in exhibit curation and symposia. Her many experiences as a panelist include the 1971 NYC's [[Art Students League of New York|Art Student's League]]'s Symposium on [[African Americans|Afro-American]] Art, the 1973, 1974 and 1976 [[National Conference of Artists]] and the NEA amongst others. She was also part of the [[Soho20 Chelsea]],<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url = https://www.nytimes.com/1993/07/31/obituaries/vivian-e-browne-64-painter-and-professor.html|title = Vivian E. Browne, 64, Painter and Professor|date = 1993-07-31|newspaper = The New York Times|issn = 0362-4331|access-date = 2016-03-05}}</ref> a [[Broome Street]] gallery. Additionally, she has been featured in over 80 group and solo exhibitions, including at the [[Museum of Modern Art|Museum of Modern Art (MoMA)]] and the [[Orlando Gallery]] and the [[Black Art Festival]] in Atlanta, Georgia.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|title=North American Women Artists of the Twentieth Century, A Biographical Dictionary|last=Heller, Jules|first=Heller, Nancy G|publisher=Garland Publishing|year=1995|isbn=0-8240-6049-0|location=New York & London|pages=[https://archive.org/details/northamericanwom00hellrich/page/93 93]|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/northamericanwom00hellrich/page/93}}</ref>\n\n==Publications==\n* 1998 SIGNS, Journal of Women in Culture and Society, Cover Illustration, published by the [[University of Chicago]]\n* 1998 African American Art, Oxford University Press pg.217\n* 1998 Not for Sale: Feminism and Art in the USA During the 1970s, a video tape and book by [[Laura Cottingham]], Hawkeye Productions, New York, NY\n* 1986 [[Heresies: A Feminist Publication on Art and Politics|Heresies]] Magazine, Illustration, 15th Issue\n* 1985 Artists and Influences, Hatch Billops\n* 1980 Heresies Magazine, Illustration, 9th Issue\n* 1979 Heresies Magazine, Photo essay on China, 8th Issue\n* 1975 Ararat Magazine, \n* 1973 Impressions, Contributor to: 8x10 Art Portfolio (1971\u201373), published by the Printmaking Workshop, New York, NY,\n* 1972 Attica Book\n* 1972 \"Afro-American Art, Annotated Bibliography\", published by the [[New York City Panel for Educational Policy|New York City Board of Education]]\n\n==Awards==\nVivian Browne was the recipient of multiple awards throughout her life.\n* [[Huntington Hartford]] Painting Fellowship, Pacific Palisades, CA, 1963\n* Achievement Award, National Association of business and Professional Women\n* Research Council Grants, Rutgers University, NJ\n* [[MacDowell Colony]] Fellowship, Peterborough, NH\t\n* Visiting Artist, [[University of California, Santa Cruz|University of California at Santa Cruz]], Santa Cruz, CA\n* Artists and Influence, Hatch-Billops Collection, New York, NY\n* Guest of Honor, [[New York Feminist Art Institute]], Women's Center for Learning, New York, NY\n* Distinguished Teacher of Art, [[College Art Association]], New York, NY\n* \"[[Ed Koch|Mayor Koch]] Honors Six Black Artists,\" City Hall, New York, NY, 1986\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.thecrowsneststudio.com/ The Crow\u2019s Nest Studio and Gallery] (Los Angeles). [http://www.thecrowsneststudio.com/artists/196-2/ partial archives of Vivian E. Browne].\n* [http://www.aaa.si.edu/collections/interviews/oral-history-interview-vivian-browne-11453 Oral History interview of Vivian Browne conducted by Henri Ghent], for the Archives of American Art. (July 1, 1968)\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{Portal bar|United States|Biography}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Browne, Vivian E}}\n[[Category:African-American artists]]\n[[Category:1993 deaths]]\n[[Category:1929 births]]\n[[Category:American expatriates in Nigeria]]\n[[Category:University of Ibadan alumni]]\n[[Category:Rutgers University faculty]]\n[[Category:American women artists]]\n[[Category:Hunter College alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Sarasota County, Florida]]\n[[Category:Artists from New York City]]\n[[Category:Art educators]]\n[[Category:20th-century American artists]]\n[[Category:American women academics]]\n[[Category:20th-century American educators]]\n[[Category:20th-century African-American activists]]\n[[Category:African-American academics]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox artist\n| honorific_prefix = \n| name             = Vivian E. Browne<!-- include middle initial, if not specified in birth_name -->\n| honorific_suffix = \n| image            = Vivian E. Browne.jpg<!-- just the pagename, without the File:/Image: prefix or [[brackets]] -->\n| image_size       = 200px\n| alt              = \n| caption          = \n| native_name      = \n| native_name_lang = \n| birth_name       = <!-- only use if different than name -->\n| birth_date       = {{Birth date|1929|04|26}}\n| birth_place      = [[Laurel, Florida]], [[United States]]\n| death_date       = {{Death date and age|1993|07|23|1929|04|26}} \n| death_place      =[[Manhattan]], [[New York (state)|New York]], United States\n| resting_place    = \n| resting_place_coordinates = <!-- {{Coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline}} -->\n| nationality      = American\n| education        = [[Hunter College]]\n| known_for        = Painting\n| notable_works    = \n| style            = \n| movement         = \n| spouse           = \n| awards           = <!-- {{awd|award|year|title|role|name}} (optional) -->\n| elected          =\n| patrons          = \n| memorials        = \n| website          = <!-- {{URL|Example.com}} -->\n| module           =\n}}\n'''Vivian E. Browne''' (April 26, 1929&ndash;July 23, 1993) was an American artist. Born in [[Laurel, Florida]], Browne was mostly known for her African-American protest paintings, and linking abstraction to nature. She has received multiple awards for her work, been an activist, professor and a founder of many galleries. According to her mother, Browne died at 64 from [[bladder cancer]].<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n==Biography==\nVivian Browne was born in [[Laurel, Florida]], on April 26, 1929.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.thecrowsneststudio.com/artists/196-2/vivian-e-browne-cv/|title = Vivian E. Browne CV|website = The Crows Nest Studio|language = en-US|access-date = 2016-03-05}}</ref> She spent most of her life in [[New York City]] and [[Kern County]], [[California]]. She received her [[Bachelor of Science]] in 1950 from [[Hunter College]], New York, NY and a [[Master of Fine Arts]] from [[Hunter College]] in 1959. Her early painting career was fostered by a scholarship from the [[New School for Social Research]], and a [[Huntington Hartford Foundation]] fellowship in 1964 and a fellowship with the [[MacDowell Colony]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nShe was invested in her travels across [[Europe]] and [[Africa]], also studying at the [[University of Ibadan]] in [[Nigeria]] in 1972. Browne worked at [[Rutgers University]] in Newark from 1971 to 1992 as a Faculty member of the Arts and Sciences department while continuing as an artist in her own right with shows across the country.\n\n== Career ==\nBrowne had multiple solo exhibitions at [[Soho20 Chelsea|SoHo 20 Gallery]] during her lifetime, as well as exhibitions at the [[Bronx Museum of the Arts|Bronx Museum]], [[University of California, Santa Cruz]] and [[Western Michigan University]].<ref>{{Cite book|title=North American Women Artists of the Twentieth Century: A Biographical Dictionary|last=Heller|first=Jules and Nancy G.|publisher=Routledge|year=1997|isbn=978-0815325840|location=Abingdon-on-Thames|pages=}}</ref> She also showed at [[MoMA PS1]]'s space in the Clocktower Gallery in 1986.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.moma.org/calendar/exhibitions/4416?locale=en|title=Progressions: A Cultural Legacy|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Browne was posthumously included in the exhibition ''We Wanted a Revolution: Black Radical Women, 1965\u201385,'' organized by the [[Brooklyn Museum]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.contemporaryartdaily.com/2017/09/group-show-at-brooklyn-museum/|title=Group Show at Brooklyn Museum|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> In 2018, her work was also shown in ''Acts of Art and Rebuttal in 1971'', an exhibition at [[Hunter College]] that revisited the 1971 exhibition ''Rebuttal to the Whitney Museum Exhibition: Black Artists in Rebuttal'' organized by members of the  Black Emergency Cultural Coalition to protest the [[Whitney Museum of American Art|Whitney Museum]]\u2019s refusal to appoint a Black curator for their survey ''Contemporary Black Artists in America''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://huntercollegeartgalleries.org/events/2018/rebuttal|title=Acts of Art and Rebuttal in 1971|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Browne had been considered for the Whitney's exhibition but was ultimately not included.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://brooklynrail.org/2018/11/artseen/Acts-of-Art-and-Rebuttal-in-1971|title=Acts of Art and Rebuttal in 1971|last=Pobric|first=Pac|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==Collections==\nBrowne's work is housed in public and private collections all over the United States, primarily in New York and California. Most notably her work can be found in the collections of the [[Smithsonian]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://americanart.si.edu/collections/search/artist/?id=624|title=Artworks Search Results / American Art|website=americanart.si.edu|access-date=2016-03-05}}</ref> with the [[Robert Blackburn (artist)]] printmaking workshop, [[MOMA]],<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.moma.org/learn/resources/archives/ps1_artists/artists_b5|title = MoMA {{!}} MoMA PS1 Artists|website = www.moma.org|access-date = 2016-03-05|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20151012011833/http://www.moma.org/learn/resources/archives/ps1_artists/artists_b5#|archive-date = 2015-10-12|url-status = dead}}</ref> the [[Schomburg Center]] NYC, [[Chase Manhattan Bank]]  the [[John Cotton Dana Library]], the Hatch-Billops Collection, the [[Wadsworth Atheneum]] Museum, The [[New York Public Library]]  and the [[Harry Belafonte]] & [[Rosa Parks]] private collections.<ref name=\":1\">Hamalian, L.. (1985). Talking to Vivian Browne. Black American Literature Forum, 19(1), 48\u201350. http://doi.org/10.2307/2904481</ref> Browne is included in the Center for the Women in the Arts and Humanities virtual exhibit at [[Rutgers University]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cwah.rutgers.edu/programs/mary-h-dana-women-artists-series/40-years-of-women-artists-at-douglass-library/virtual-exhibit/#B|title=Center for Women in the Arts and Humanities|website=cwah.rutgers.edu|access-date=2016-03-05}}</ref>\n\n==Activism==\nMany of Browne's works, particularly those from the 1960s, showcase her dissatisfaction with the struggles of growing up as a [[Disfranchisement|disenfranchised]] black woman. \"Black art is political. If it's not political, it's not black art\".<ref name=\":1\" /> While she fought for equality, she was not optimistic about attitudes changing soon, and self categorized her look at art into two categories. \"When I am political, I am painting as a black or as a woman or both. Otherwise, I am just a member of the human race.\" She taught the History of Black Art at [[Rutgers University]], and served as chair of the department from 1975-1978. \n\nBrowne contributed to, and served as an advisor to, ''[[Heresies: A Feminist Publication on Art and Politics|HERESIES: A Feminist Publication on Art and Politics]]'', including serving on the editorial collective for issue #15, Racism is the Issue. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://archive.org/stream/heresies_20/heresies_20_djvu.txt|title=Full text of \"Heresies Magazine Issue #20: Heresies (Volume 5, Number 4)\"|website=archive.org|access-date=2016-03-05}}</ref>\n\n==Major Achievements==\nIn addition to serving as a professor and department chair at [[Rutgers]], Browne was honored most notably for her political works showcasing her life as a black woman. She served as a [[Fulbright]] panelist in 1990, and spent much of her time in the 70s and 80s in exhibit curation and symposia. Her many experiences as a panelist include the 1971 NYC's [[Art Students League of New York|Art Student's League]]'s Symposium on [[African Americans|Afro-American]] Art, the 1973, 1974 and 1976 [[National Conference of Artists]] and the NEA amongst others. She was also part of the [[Soho20 Chelsea]],<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url = https://www.nytimes.com/1993/07/31/obituaries/vivian-e-browne-64-painter-and-professor.html|title = Vivian E. Browne, 64, Painter and Professor|date = 1993-07-31|newspaper = The New York Times|issn = 0362-4331|access-date = 2016-03-05}}</ref> a [[Broome Street]] gallery. Additionally, she has been featured in over 80 group and solo exhibitions, including at the [[Museum of Modern Art|Museum of Modern Art (MoMA)]] and the [[Orlando Gallery]] and the [[Black Art Festival]] in Atlanta, Georgia.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|title=North American Women Artists of the Twentieth Century, A Biographical Dictionary|last=Heller, Jules|first=Heller, Nancy G|publisher=Garland Publishing|year=1995|isbn=0-8240-6049-0|location=New York & London|pages=[https://archive.org/details/northamericanwom00hellrich/page/93 93]|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/northamericanwom00hellrich/page/93}}</ref>\n\n==Publications==\n* 1998 SIGNS, Journal of Women in Culture and Society, Cover Illustration, published by the [[University of Chicago]]\n* 1998 African American Art, Oxford University Press pg.217\n* 1998 Not for Sale: Feminism and Art in the USA During the 1970s, a video tape and book by [[Laura Cottingham]], Hawkeye Productions, New York, NY\n* 1986 [[Heresies: A Feminist Publication on Art and Politics|Heresies]] Magazine, Illustration, 15th Issue\n* 1985 Artists and Influences, Hatch Billops\n* 1980 Heresies Magazine, Illustration, 9th Issue\n* 1979 Heresies Magazine, Photo essay on China, 8th Issue\n* 1975 Ararat Magazine, \n* 1973 Impressions, Contributor to: 8x10 Art Portfolio (1971\u201373), published by the Printmaking Workshop, New York, NY,\n* 1972 Attica Book\n* 1972 \"Afro-American Art, Annotated Bibliography\", published by the [[New York City Panel for Educational Policy|New York City Board of Education]]\n\n==Awards==\nVivian Browne was the recipient of multiple awards throughout her life.\n* [[Huntington Hartford]] Painting Fellowship, Pacific Palisades, CA, 1963\n* Achievement Award, National Association of Business and Professional Women\n* Research Council Grants, Rutgers University, NJ\n* [[MacDowell Colony]] Fellowship, Peterborough, NH\t\n* Visiting Artist, [[University of California, Santa Cruz|University of California at Santa Cruz]], Santa Cruz, CA\n* Artists and Influence, Hatch-Billops Collection, New York, NY\n* Guest of Honor, [[New York Feminist Art Institute]], Women's Center for Learning, New York, NY\n* Distinguished Teacher of Art, [[College Art Association]], New York, NY\n* \"[[Ed Koch|Mayor Koch]] Honors Six Black Artists,\" City Hall, New York, NY, 1986\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.thecrowsneststudio.com/ The Crow\u2019s Nest Studio and Gallery] (Los Angeles). [http://www.thecrowsneststudio.com/artists/196-2/ partial archives of Vivian E. Browne].\n* [http://www.aaa.si.edu/collections/interviews/oral-history-interview-vivian-browne-11453 Oral History interview of Vivian Browne conducted by Henri Ghent], for the Archives of American Art. (July 1, 1968)\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{Portal bar|United States|Biography}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Browne, Vivian E}}\n[[Category:African-American artists]]\n[[Category:1993 deaths]]\n[[Category:1929 births]]\n[[Category:American expatriates in Nigeria]]\n[[Category:University of Ibadan alumni]]\n[[Category:Rutgers University faculty]]\n[[Category:American women artists]]\n[[Category:Hunter College alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Sarasota County, Florida]]\n[[Category:Artists from New York City]]\n[[Category:Art educators]]\n[[Category:20th-century American artists]]\n[[Category:American women academics]]\n[[Category:20th-century American educators]]\n[[Category:20th-century African-American activists]]\n[[Category:African-American academics]]\n", "name_user": "Chris the speller", "label": "safe", "comment": "replaced: Business \u2192 business, Faculty \u2192 faculty, 1975-1978 \u2192 1975 to 1978", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vivian_E._Browne"}
