{"title_page": "Alessandro Lualdi", "text_new": "{{unreferenced|date=June 2018}}\n{{Infobox Christian leader\n|type                = Cardinal\n|honorific_prefix    = [[His Eminence]]\n|name                = Alessandro Lualdi\n|image               = Alessandro Lualdi-1922.jpg\n|caption             = Lualdi in 1922.\n|title               = [[Cardinal (Catholicism) | Cardinal]], [[Archbishop of Palermo]]\n|church              = [[Roman Catholic Church]]\n|archdiocese         = Palermo\n|see                 = Palermo\n|appointed           = 14 November 1904\n|term_end            = 12 November 1927\n|predecessor         = [[Michelangelo Celesia]]\n|successor           = [[Luigi Lavitrano]]\n|other_post          = [[Santi Andrea e Gregorio al Monte Celio|Cardinal-Priest of Santi Andrea e Gregorio al Monte Celio]] (1907-27)\n|ordination          = 30 October 1880\n|consecration        = 4 December 1904\n|consecrated_by      = [[Francesco di Paola Cassetta]]\n|cardinal            = 15 April 1907\n|created_cardinal_by = [[Pope Pius X]]\n|rank                = [[Cardinal-Priest]]\n|birth_name          = Alessandro Lualdi\n|birth_date          = 12 August 1858\n|birth_place         = [[Milan]], [[Kingdom of Lombardy-Venetia]]\n|death_date          = {{Death date and age|df=yes|1927|11|12|1858|08|12}}\n|death_place         = [[Palermo]], [[Kingdom of Italy]]\n|buried              = [[Palermo Cathedral]]\n|alma_mater          = [[Pontifical University of Saint Thomas Aquinas]]\n|previous_post       = Rector of the Pontifical Lombard Seminary (1894-1904) }}\n\n{{infobox cardinalstyles|\ncardinal name=Alessandro Lualdi |\ndipstyle=His Eminence|\noffstyle=Your Eminence|\nSee=Palermo|}}\n\n'''Alessandro Lualdi''' [[Doctor of Canon Law|J.C.D.]] [[Doctor of Sacred Theology|S.T.D.]] (12 August 1858 \u2013 12 November 1927) was an [[Italian people|Italian]] [[Roman Catholic]] [[Cardinal (Catholic Church)|cardinal]] who served as [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Palermo|Archbishop of Palermo]]. \n\n==Biography==\nLualdi was born in [[Milan]], [[Italy]]. He entered the [[Seminary]] of Milan and carried on further studies at the [[Angelicum|Theological Academy of Saint Thomas Aquinas]] in [[Rome]] where he earned [[doctorate]]s in [[theology]], [[philosophy]] and [[canon law]]. He was ordained in 1880. After his ordination, he worked in the Archdiocese of Milan doing pastoral work from 1884 until 1890. He later served as a faculty member of the Seminary of Milan until 1894. He was created [[Monsignor|Privy Chamberlain of His Holiness]] on 14 September 1899. \n\n==Episcopate==\n[[Pope Pius X]] appointed him [[Archbishop]] of [[Palermo]] on 14 November 1904. He was created and proclaimed [[Cardinal-Priest]] of ''[[Santi Andrea e Gregorio al Monte Celio]]'' in the [[Papal consistory|consistory]] of 15 April 1907. He took part in the [[Papal conclave|conclave]]s of [[Papal conclave, 1914|1914]] that elected [[Pope Benedict XV]] and [[Papal conclave, 1922|1922]] that elected [[Pope Pius XI]]. \n\nHe died in 1927 and is buried in the metropolitan cathedral of Palermo.\n\n==References==\n<!--- See [[Wikipedia:Footnotes]] on how to create references using <ref></ref> tags which will then appear here automatically -->\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{start box}}\n{{s-rel|ca}}\n{{succession box |\nbefore=[[Michelangelo Celesia]] |\ntitle=[[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Palermo|Archbishop of Palermo]]|\nafter=[[Luigi Lavitrano]] |\nyears=14 November 1904&ndash;12 November 1927}}\n{{end box}}\n\n{{Subject bar |portal1= Biography |portal2= Catholicism |portal3= Italy}}\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lualdi, Alessandro}}\n[[Category:1858 births]]\n[[Category:1927 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Milan]]\n[[Category:Italian cardinals]]\n[[Category:Roman Catholic archbishops of Palermo]]\n[[Category:20th-century Roman Catholic archbishops]]\n[[Category:Cardinals created by Pope Pius X]]\n", "text_old": "{{unreferenced|date=June 2018}}\n{{Infobox Christian leader\n|type                = Cardinal\n|honorific_prefix    = [[His Eminence]]\n|name                = Alessandro Lualdi\n|image               = Alessandro Lualdi-1922.jpg\n|caption             = Lualdi in 1922.\n|title               = [[Cardinal (Catholicism) | Cardinal]], [[Archbishop of Palermo]]\n|church              = [[Roman Catholic Church]]\n|archdiocese         = Palermo\n|see                 = Palermo\n|appointed           = 14 November 1904\n|term_end            = 12 November 1927\n|predecessor         = [[Michelangelo Celesia]]\n|successor           = [[Luigi Lavitrano]]\n|other_post          = [[Santi Andrea e Gregorio al Monte Celio|Cardinal-Priest of Santi Andrea e Gregorio al Monte Celio]] (1907-27)\n|ordination          = 30 October 1880\n|consecration        = 4 December 1904\n|consecrated_by      = [[Francesco di Paola Cassetta]]\n|cardinal            = 15 April 1907\n|created_cardinal_by = [[Pope Pius X]]\n|rank                = [[Cardinal-Priest]]\n|birth_name          = Alessandro Lualdi\n|birth_date          = 12 August 1858\n|birth_place         = [[Milan]], [[Kingdom of Lombardy-Venetia]]\n|death_date          = {{Death date and age|df=yes|1927|11|12|1858|08|12}}\n|death_place         = [[Palermo]], [[Kingdom of Italy]]\n|buried              = [[Palermo Cathedral]]\n|alma_mater          = [[Pontifical University of Saint Thomas Aquinas]]\n|previous_post       = Rector of the Pontifical Lombard Seminary (1894-1904) }}\n\n{{infobox cardinalstyles|\ncardinal name=Alessandro Lualdi |\ndipstyle=His Eminence|\noffstyle=Your Eminence|\nSee=Palermo|}}\n\n'''Alessandro Lualdi''' [[Doctor of Canon Law|J.C.D.]] [[Doctor of Sacred Theology|S.T.D.]] (12 August 1858 - 12 November 1927) was an [[Italian people|Italian]] [[Roman Catholic]] [[Cardinal (Catholic Church)|cardinal]] who served as [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Palermo|Archbishop of Palermo]]. \n\n==Biography==\nLualdi was born in [[Milan]], [[Italy]]. He entered the [[Seminary]] of Milan and carried on further studies at the [[Angelicum|Theological Academy of Saint Thomas Aquinas]] in [[Rome]] where he earned [[doctorate]]s in [[theology]], [[philosophy]] and [[canon law]]. He was ordained in 1880. After his ordination, he worked in the Archdiocese of Milan doing pastoral work from 1884 until 1890. He later served as a Faculty member of the Seminary of Milan until 1894. He was created [[Monsignor|Privy Chamberlain of His Holiness]] on 14 September 1899. \n\n==Episcopate==\n[[Pope Pius X]] appointed him [[Archbishop]] of [[Palermo]] on 14 November 1904. He was created and proclaimed [[Cardinal-Priest]] of ''[[Santi Andrea e Gregorio al Monte Celio]]'' in the [[Papal consistory|consistory]] of 15 April 1907. He took part in the [[Papal conclave|conclave]]s of [[Papal conclave, 1914|1914]] that elected [[Pope Benedict XV]] and [[Papal conclave, 1922|1922]] that elected [[Pope Pius XI]]. \n\nHe died in 1927 and is buried in the metropolitan cathedral of Palermo.\n\n==References==\n<!--- See [[Wikipedia:Footnotes]] on how to create references using <ref></ref> tags which will then appear here automatically -->\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{start box}}\n{{s-rel|ca}}\n{{succession box |\nbefore=[[Michelangelo Celesia]] |\ntitle=[[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Palermo|Archbishop of Palermo]]|\nafter=[[Luigi Lavitrano]] |\nyears=14 November 1904&ndash;12 November 1927}}\n{{end box}}\n\n{{Subject bar |portal1= Biography |portal2= Catholicism |portal3= Italy}}\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lualdi, Alessandro}}\n[[Category:1858 births]]\n[[Category:1927 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Milan]]\n[[Category:Italian cardinals]]\n[[Category:Roman Catholic archbishops of Palermo]]\n[[Category:20th-century Roman Catholic archbishops]]\n[[Category:Cardinals created by Pope Pius X]]\n", "name_user": "Chris the speller", "label": "safe", "comment": "replaced: -  \u2192  \u2013 , Faculty \u2192 faculty", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alessandro_Lualdi"}
{"title_page": "Nell Gwynn House", "text_new": "{{Infobox building\n| name = Nell Gwynn House\n| native_name=\n| image = Nell Gwynn House (geograph 4181254).jpg\n| caption = \n| former_names =\n| alternate_names = \n| building_type = Residential buildings\n| architectural_style = [[Art Deco architecture|Art Deco]]\n| structural_system =\n| cost =\n| location = [[Sloane Avenue]]\n| address             = \n| location_town       = [[Chelsea, London]]\n| location_country    = United Kingdom\n| iso_region          = \n| client = \n| owner = \n| current_tenants =\n| landlord =\n| coordinates =\n| altitude =\n| start_date = 1936\n| completion_date = 1937\n| inauguration_date =\n| demolition_date =\n| height = \n| diameter =\n| other_dimensions = \n| floor_count =\n| floor_area =\n| main_contractor =\n| architect = [[G. Kay Green]]\n| structural_engineer =\n| services_engineer =\n| civil_engineer =\n| other_designers =\n| quantity_surveyor =\n| awards =\n| references =\n}}\n'''Nell Gwynn House''' is a ten-storey residential building in [[Sloane Avenue]], [[Chelsea, London]], designed in the [[Art Deco architecture|Art Deco style]] by [[G. Kay Green]]. Completed in 1937, it stands next to the same architect's [[Sloane Avenue Mansions]], built a few years earlier.\n\n==History==\nIn the 1840s, there was a house on the site of Nell Gwynn House in which the member of parliament [[George Thompson (abolitionist)|George Thompson]] lived. A [[blue plaque]] added to the side of the present building in 2013 commemorates Thompson being visited there in 1846 by the notable American [[Frederick Douglass]].<ref name=home/>\n\nAt the beginning of the 20th century, this area of Chelsea contained run-down or derelict housing, and by the 1930s the area was being redeveloped.<ref>Brian Girling, ''Chelsea Through Time'' (Amberley Publishing, Stroud, 2015, {{ISBN|9781445634999}}), p. 137</ref> The [[Victoria County History]] notes that by the end of the decade the district was \"filled with housing for the better off, a curious mixture of select, consciously picturesque low houses and enormous and forbidding blocks of flats, either cautiously Art Deco or approximately neoGeorgian in style.\" It continues:\n{{Quote|On the east side of Sloane Avenue several semi-detached houses were built and two immense ten-storeyed blocks of flats on either side of Whitehead's Grove with second frontages to Draycott Avenue: on the south corner Sloane Avenue Mansions was completed in 1933, and on the north corner the larger Nell Gwynne House, faced with red brick and with a spacious open courtyard in the centre forming the main entrance, was finished in 1937. Both had parking space in the basements, and Nell Gwynn House had a restaurant open to non-residents.<ref name=vch>''A History of the County of Middlesex, volume 12'' (Victoria County History, 2004) [http://www.british-history.ac.uk/vch/middx/vol12/pp79-90 pp. 79-90]</ref>}}\n\nWith a footprint forming a giant capital W, the building's geometric design was [[Cubism|Cubist]], making use of Egyptian, Aztec, and Mayan patterns and materials. From the outset, each apartment had built-in central heating, there was a restaurant in the basement, a hairdressing salon, and a bar in the lobby.<ref name=home>[https://www.nellgwynnchelsea.london Nell Gwynn Chelsea] homepage, accessed 25 July 2016</ref>\n\nIn 1937, ''Country Life'' carried an advertisement -\n\n{{Quote|\"NOT HAVE A DISTINCTIVE FLAT IN TOWN? The Supreme choice : NELL GWYNN HOUSE CHELSEA'S SMARTEST BUILDING Inclusive Rentals \u00a390 to \u00a3190 per annum Nell Gwynn House offers beautifully designed and decorated single-roomed and two-roomed flats, each with their own private bathroom, kitchenette and up-to-date conveniences for luxurious comfort. Magnificent Restaurant - Ballroom for 200 Patrons. Cocktail and Snack Bar which are definitely unique. Perfect service: well trained staff.\"<ref>''Country Life'', Volume 82 (1937), p. 527</ref>}}\n\nIn 1946, under the Labour government's [[Furnished Houses (Rent Control) Act 1946]], the new Chelsea, Holborn and Westminster Rent Tribunal was asked by tenants to assess the fair rent of two flats in Nell Gwynn House. The landlord had wanted to increase the rent to \u00a35 5s a week, but the Tribunal imposed rents of \u00a34-1s-6d and \u00a34-2s-6d in the two cases.<ref>''The Estates Gazette Digest of Land and Property Cases 1946'' (Estates Gazette, 1947), pp. 36-39: \"Chelsea, Holborn and Westminster Rent Tribunal \u2014 Mr. C. William Skinner, J.P., Barrister-at-law (Chairman); Mr. G. M. Cunningham, Barrister-at-Law; and Mrs. A. B. Martin... Furnished Houses (Rent Control) Act, 1946 \u2014 Nell Gwynn House, Chelsea \u2014 First public hearing...\"</ref> The landlord was Nell Gwynn Furnished Flats Ltd., which then controlled seventy-nine unfurnished flats in the building, out of a total of 437 self-contained flats.<ref>''Justice of the Peace and Local Government Review'', Volume 110 (Justice of the Peace, Ltd, 1946), p. 481</ref>\n\nIn 1948, a music club was established, with [[Adrian Boult|Sir Adrian Boult]] as President, and was patronised by [[Vaughan Williams]], [[Arnold Bax]], and [[John Ireland (composer)|John Ireland]].<ref name=home/>\n\nIn 1966, A. G. Ogden described Nell Gwynn House as a \"pied a terre for many Chelsea bachelors who honor the spirit of [[Charles II of England|Charles II]].<ref>Archibald G. Ogden, ''London for everyone: an informal guide'' (1966), p. 136</ref> In 1967, three Scandinavian newspapers were using apartment 337 as their London contact address,<ref>''Willing's Press Guide'' (T. Skinner Directories, 1967), pp. 574, 575, 593: ''[[Arbetet]]'' of [[Malm\u00f6]], ''[[S\u00f8rlandet (newspaper)|S\u00f8rlandet]]'' of [[Kristiansand]], and ''Nordlands Framtid'' of [[Bod\u00f8]]</ref> joined by two others in 1971.<ref>''Willing's Press Guide'' (T. Skinner Directories, 1971), pp 534, 535, 574: ''Jysk Aktuelt'' of [[Horsens]] and ''Bornholmeren'' of [[R\u00f8nne]]</ref>\n\nIn a taxation case in the [[High Court of Justice|High Court]] in 1966, Mr Justice Megarry concluded: \u201cI am certainly unable to say that, as a matter of law, the Special Commissioners were wrong in being unable in these circumstances to find in Nell Gwynn House sufficient of the qualities of an investment  to enable them to say that it was indeed an investment.\u201d<ref>Reports of Tax Cases, Volume 45 (H. M. Stationery Office, 1966), p. 198</ref>\n\n==Management Company and freehold==\n[[File:Scaffolding Nell Gwynn House, Chelsea - geograph.org.uk - 1189489.jpg|thumb|160px|Scaffolding in place for renovation work in 2009]]\n\nOn 29 September 1937, the Central London Property Trust Ltd granted a lease of the whole block of flats to Nell Gwynn House (Chelsea) Ltd for ninety-nine years at a rent of \u00a37,000 a year, and on the same day the company borrowed \u00a3225,000 from Land Charges Ltd, mortgaging its lease.<ref>''The Accountant'', Volume 158 (Lafferty Publications, Limited, 1968), p. 784</ref>\n\nSince 2006, the Trustees of the building have undertaken a major refurbishment, inside and out, including the renovation of more than half of the apartments and the restoration of the Art-Deco features in the reception and public areas, by interior designer [[Tim Gosling]].<ref name=home/>\n\nIn 2010, NGH Freehold Ltd, a management company representing about three-quarters of the lessees, bought the freehold (see [[collective enfranchisement]]) which lowered the cost for the lessees of licences to make any major alterations or other works.  At the time of the sale to NGH Freehold Ltd, this was the largest UK collective enfranchisement.\n\n==Statue and alcove==\nAbove the main entrance, at the level of the 2nd floor, is [[Nell Gwynn]]'s statue, with a [[Cavalier King Charles spaniel]] at her feet. This stands at the foot of an alcove six storeys high, topped by an art deco set of reliefs, and is hard to see from Sloane Avenue, so is mostly unnoticed by the traffic, but it is believed to be the only statue of a [[royal mistress]] anywhere in the capital city.<ref>[http://knowledgeoflondon.com/rooftops.html Rooftop statues] at knowledgeoflondon.com/rooftops, accessed 13 January 2018</ref>\n\n==Notable residents==\n*[[Frank Foley]] (1884\u20131958), [[Secret Intelligence Service]] officer who helped many Jewish families to escape from Germany in the 1930s<ref>Michael Smith, ''Foley: the Spy who Saved 10,000 Jews'' (2016), [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=jWHzCwAAQBAJ&pg=PT177#v=onepage&q&f=false p. 177]</ref>\n*[[Daisy Burrell]] (1892\u20131982), actress of the silent film era, lived in flat 203 as Daisy Young<ref>Probate index for 1982 at probatesearch.gov.uk, accessed 22 July 2016: \"Young, Daisy Isobel Eaglesfield Ratton otherwise Daisy Isobel Eaglesfield of 203 Nell Gwynn House Sloane Av London SW3 died 10 June 1982.\"</ref>\n*[[Vera Atkins]] (1908\u20132000), Romanian-born Intelligence Officer of the Second World War<ref name=home/> occupied Flat 725 between 1940 and 1950\n*[[Theyre Lee-Elliott]] (1903\u20131988), artist, designer of the [[British Overseas Airways Corporation|BOAC]] [[Speedbird]]<ref name=home/>\n*[[Samuel Hughes (judge)|Samuel Hughes]] (1913\u20132002), Canadian field historian, during Second World War<ref>Sam Hughes, ''Steering the Course: A Memoir'' (McGill-Queen's Press, 2000), Chapter 10</ref>\n*[[Diana Dors]] (1931\u20131984) English film actress and singer.\n*[[Great Train Robbery (1963)#Robbers and accomplices|Roy James]] (1935\u20131997), one of the Great Train robbers, was living in flat 907 at the time of the robbery in 1963<ref name=home/>\n*[[Bruce Forsyth]] (1928\u20132017), entertainer<ref name=home/> occupied Flat 832 until 2000\n* Tina Moore, first wife of footballer [[Bobby Moore]]\n\nIn February 2013, a [[blue plaque]] was unveiled by [[Barbara J. Stephenson]], the deputy high commissioner at the [[United States Embassy in London]], in honour of the social reformer and abolitionist [[Frederick Douglass]]. It is located on the Whiteheads Grove elevation of the block, standing on the site of the London house of the British abolitionist [[George Thompson (abolitionist)|George Thompson]], with whom Douglass stayed in 1846, while lecturing in London.\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{coord|51.4922|-0.1650|display=title}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nell Gwynn House}}\n[[Category:Chelsea, London]]\n[[Category:Residential buildings in London]]\n[[Category:Residential buildings completed in 1937]]\n[[Category:Art Deco architecture in London]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox building\n| name = Nell Gwynn House\n| native_name=\n| image = Nell Gwynn House (geograph 4181254).jpg\n| caption = \n| former_names =\n| alternate_names = \n| building_type = Residential buildings\n| architectural_style = [[Art Deco architecture|Art Deco]]\n| structural_system =\n| cost =\n| location = [[Sloane Avenue]]\n| address             = \n| location_town       = [[Chelsea, London]]\n| location_country    = United Kingdom\n| iso_region          = \n| client = \n| owner = \n| current_tenants =\n| landlord =\n| coordinates =\n| altitude =\n| start_date = 1936\n| completion_date = 1937\n| inauguration_date =\n| demolition_date =\n| height = \n| diameter =\n| other_dimensions = \n| floor_count =\n| floor_area =\n| main_contractor =\n| architect = [[G. Kay Green]]\n| structural_engineer =\n| services_engineer =\n| civil_engineer =\n| other_designers =\n| quantity_surveyor =\n| awards =\n| references =\n}}\n'''Nell Gwynn House''' is a ten-storey residential building in [[Sloane Avenue]], [[Chelsea, London]], designed in the [[Art Deco architecture|Art Deco style]] by [[G. Kay Green]]. Completed in 1937, it stands next to the same architect's [[Sloane Avenue Mansions]], built a few years earlier.\n\n==History==\nIn the 1840s, there was a house on the site of Nell Gwynn House in which the member of parliament [[George Thompson (abolitionist)|George Thompson]] lived. A [[blue plaque]] added to the side of the present building in 2013 commemorates Thompson being visited there in 1846 by the notable American [[Frederick Douglass]].<ref name=home/>\n\nAt the beginning of the 20th century, this area of Chelsea contained run-down or derelict housing, and by the 1930s the area was being redeveloped.<ref>Brian Girling, ''Chelsea Through Time'' (Amberley Publishing, Stroud, 2015, {{ISBN|9781445634999}}), p. 137</ref> The [[Victoria County History]] notes that by the end of the decade the district was \"filled with housing for the better off, a curious mixture of select, consciously picturesque low houses and enormous and forbidding blocks of flats, either cautiously Art Deco or approximately neoGeorgian in style.\" It continues:\n{{Quote|On the east side of Sloane Avenue several semi-detached houses were built and two immense ten-storeyed blocks of flats on either side of Whitehead's Grove with second frontages to Draycott Avenue: on the south corner Sloane Avenue Mansions was completed in 1933, and on the north corner the larger Nell Gwynne House, faced with red brick and with a spacious open courtyard in the centre forming the main entrance, was finished in 1937. Both had parking space in the basements, and Nell Gwynn House had a restaurant open to non-residents.<ref name=vch>''A History of the County of Middlesex, volume 12'' (Victoria County History, 2004) [http://www.british-history.ac.uk/vch/middx/vol12/pp79-90 pp. 79-90]</ref>}}\n\nWith a footprint forming a giant capital W, the building's geometric design was [[Cubism|Cubist]], making use of Egyptian, Aztec, and Mayan patterns and materials. From the outset, each apartment had built-in central heating, there was a restaurant in the basement, a hairdressing salon, and a bar in the lobby.<ref name=home>[https://www.nellgwynnchelsea.london Nell Gwynn Chelsea] homepage, accessed 25 July 2016</ref>\n\nIn 1937, ''Country Life'' carried an advertisement -\n\n{{Quote|\"NOT HAVE A DISTINCTIVE FLAT IN TOWN? The Supreme choice : NELL GWYNN HOUSE CHELSEA'S SMARTEST BUILDING Inclusive Rentals \u00a390 to \u00a3190 per annum Nell Gwynn House offers beautifully designed and decorated single-roomed and two-roomed flats, each with their own private bathroom, kitchenette and up-to-date conveniences for luxurious comfort. Magnificent Restaurant - Ballroom for 200 Patrons. Cocktail and Snack Bar which are definitely unique. Perfect service: well trained staff.\"<ref>''Country Life'', Volume 82 (1937), p. 527</ref>}}\n\nIn 1946, under the Labour government's [[Furnished Houses (Rent Control) Act 1946]], the new Chelsea, Holborn and Westminster Rent Tribunal was asked by tenants to assess the fair rent of two flats in Nell Gwynn House. The landlord had wanted to increase the rent to \u00a35 5s a week, but the Tribunal imposed rents of \u00a34-1s-6d and \u00a34-2s-6d in the two cases.<ref>''The Estates Gazette Digest of Land and Property Cases 1946'' (Estates Gazette, 1947), pp. 36-39: \"Chelsea, Holborn and Westminster Rent Tribunal \u2014 Mr. C. William Skinner, J.P., Barrister-at-law (Chairman); Mr. G. M. Cunningham, Barrister-at-Law; and Mrs. A. B. Martin... Furnished Houses (Rent Control) Act, 1946 \u2014 Nell Gwynn House, Chelsea \u2014 First public hearing...\"</ref> The landlord was Nell Gwynn Furnished Flats Ltd., which then controlled seventy-nine unfurnished flats in the building, out of a total of 437 self-contained flats.<ref>''Justice of the Peace and Local Government Review'', Volume 110 (Justice of the Peace, Ltd, 1946), p. 481</ref>\n\nIn 1948, a music club was established, with [[Adrian Boult|Sir Adrian Boult]] as President, and was patronised by [[Vaughan Williams]], [[Arnold Bax]], and [[John Ireland (composer)|John Ireland]].<ref name=home/>\n\nIn 1966, A. G. Ogden described Nell Gwynn House as a \"pied a terre for many Chelsea bachelors who honor the spirit of [[Charles II of England|Charles II]].<ref>Archibald G. Ogden, ''London for everyone: an informal guide'' (1966), p. 136</ref> In 1967, three Scandinavian newspapers were using apartment 337 as their London contact address,<ref>''Willing's Press Guide'' (T. Skinner Directories, 1967), pp. 574, 575, 593: ''[[Arbetet]]'' of [[Malm\u00f6]], ''[[S\u00f8rlandet (newspaper)|S\u00f8rlandet]]'' of [[Kristiansand]], and ''Nordlands Framtid'' of [[Bod\u00f8]]</ref> joined by two others in 1971.<ref>''Willing's Press Guide'' (T. Skinner Directories, 1971), pp 534, 535, 574: ''Jysk Aktuelt'' of [[Horsens]] and ''Bornholmeren'' of [[R\u00f8nne]]</ref>\n\nIn a taxation case in the [[High Court of Justice|High Court]] in 1966, Mr Justice Megarry concluded: \u201cI am certainly unable to say that, as a matter of law, the Special Commissioners were wrong in being unable in these circumstances to find in Nell Gwynn House sufficient of the qualities of an investment  to enable them to say that it was indeed an investment.\u201d<ref>Reports of Tax Cases, Volume 45 (H. M. Stationery Office, 1966), p. 198</ref>\n\n==Management Company and freehold==\n[[File:Scaffolding Nell Gwynn House, Chelsea - geograph.org.uk - 1189489.jpg|thumb|160px|Scaffolding in place for renovation work in 2009]]\n\nOn 29 September 1937, the Central London Property Trust Ltd granted a lease of the whole block of flats to Nell Gwynn House (Chelsea) Ltd for ninety-nine years at a rent of \u00a37,000 a year, and on the same day the company borrowed \u00a3225,000 from Land Charges Ltd, mortgaging its lease.<ref>''The Accountant'', Volume 158 (Lafferty Publications, Limited, 1968), p. 784</ref>\n\nSince 2006, the Trustees of the building have undertaken a major refurbishment, inside and out, including the renovation of more than half of the apartments and the restoration of the Art-Deco features in the reception and public areas, by interior designer [[Tim Gosling]].<ref name=home/>\n\nIn 2010, NGH Freehold Ltd, a management company representing about three-quarters of the lessees, bought the freehold (see [[collective enfranchisement]]) which lowered the cost for the lessees of licences to make any major alterations or other works.  At the time of the sale to NGH Freehold Ltd, this was the largest UK collective enfranchisement.\n\n==Statue and alcove==\nAbove the main entrance, at the level of the 2nd floor, is [[Nell Gwynn]]'s statue, with a [[Cavalier King Charles spaniel]] at her feet. This stands at the foot of an alcove six storeys high, topped by an art deco set of reliefs, and is hard to see from Sloane Avenue, so is mostly unnoticed by the traffic, but it is believed to be the only statue of a [[royal mistress]] anywhere in the capital city.<ref>[http://knowledgeoflondon.com/rooftops.html Rooftop statues] at knowledgeoflondon.com/rooftops, accessed 13 January 2018</ref>\n\n==Notable residents==\n*[[Frank Foley]] (1884\u20131958), [[Secret Intelligence Service]] officer who helped many Jewish families to escape from Germany in the 1930s<ref>Michael Smith, ''Foley: the Spy who Saved 10,000 Jews'' (2016), [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=jWHzCwAAQBAJ&pg=PT177#v=onepage&q&f=false p. 177]</ref>\n*[[Daisy Burrell]] (1892\u20131982), actress of the silent film era, lived in flat 203 as Daisy Young<ref>Probate index for 1982 at probatesearch.gov.uk, accessed 22 July 2016: \"Young, Daisy Isobel Eaglesfield Ratton otherwise Daisy Isobel Eaglesfield of 203 Nell Gwynn House Sloane Av London SW3 died 10 June 1982.\"</ref>\n*[[Vera Atkins]] (1908\u20132000), Romanian-born Intelligence Officer of the Second World War<ref name=home/> occupied Flat 725 between 1940 and 1950\n*[[Theyre Lee-Elliott]] (1903\u20131988), artist, designer of the [[British Overseas Airways Corporation|BOAC]] [[Speedbird]]<ref name=home/>\n*[[Samuel Hughes (judge)|Samuel Hughes]] (1913\u20132002), Canadian field historian, during Second World War<ref>Sam Hughes, ''Steering the Course: A Memoir'' (McGill-Queen's Press, 2000), Chapter 10</ref>\n*[[Diana Dors]] (1931\u20131984) English film actress and singer.\n*[[Great Train Robbery (1963)#Robbers and accomplices|Roy James]] (1935\u20131997), one of the Great Train robbers, was living in flat 907 at the time of the robbery in 1963<ref name=home/>\n*[[Bruce Forsyth]] (1928\u20132017), entertainer<ref name=home/> occupied Flat 832 until 2000\n* Tina Moore, first wife of footballer [[Bobby Moore]]\n\nIn February 2013, a blue heritage plaque was unveiled by [[Barbara J. Stephenson]], the deputy high commissioner of the United States Embassy in London, in honour of the social reformer and abolitionist [[Frederick Douglass]]. It is located on the Whiteheads Grove elevation of the block, standing on the site of the London house of the British abolitionist [[George Thompson (abolitionist)|George Thompson]], with whom Douglass stayed in 1846, while lecturing in London.\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{coord|51.4922|-0.1650|display=title}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nell Gwynn House}}\n[[Category:Chelsea, London]]\n[[Category:Residential buildings in London]]\n[[Category:Residential buildings completed in 1937]]\n[[Category:Art Deco architecture in London]]\n", "name_user": "Moonraker", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eNotable residents", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nell_Gwynn_House"}
